```cpp
#include <hexi/hexi.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>
#include <span>

std::vector<uint32_t> read_item_batch(const std::span<const uint8_t> buffer) {
    // Create a read-only buffer adaptor from the span
    hexi::buffer_adaptor adaptor(buffer);

    // Create a binary stream for reading
    hexi::binary_stream stream(adaptor);

    // Read the item_count (uint32_t)
    uint32_t item_count = stream.get<uint32_t>();

    // Use get() to read the container of uint32_t values
    // The get() method with a container type and count will read the specified number of elements
    std::vector<uint32_t> items = stream.get<std::vector<uint32_t>>(item_count);

    return items;
}
```

The key points from the code fragments:
- `hexi::buffer_adaptor` wraps various buffer types (including `std::span`)
- `hexi::binary_stream` is used for serialization/deserialization
- The `get()` method is used to read data from the stream
- For containers, you can specify the type and count to read multiple elements

This implementation follows the pattern shown in examples like `span_deserialisation.cpp` and `serialise_custom_type.cpp` where `binary_stream` is used to read data from a buffer adaptor.

