Looking at the provided code fragments, I can see that the Hexi library provides endianness conversion functionality through the `hexi::endian::conditional_reverse` function. Here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/endian.h>
#include <cstdint>
#include <bit>

template<typename T>
T convert_to_big_endian(T value) {
    return hexi::endian::conditional_reverse(value, std::endian::native, std::endian::big);
}

template<typename T>
T convert_from_big_endian(T value) {
    return hexi::endian::conditional_reverse(value, std::endian::big, std::endian::native);
}

template<typename T>
T convert_to_little_endian(T value) {
    return hexi::endian::conditional_reverse(value, std::endian::native, std::endian::little);
}

template<typename T>
T convert_from_little_endian(T value) {
    return hexi::endian::conditional_reverse(value, std::endian::little, std::endian::native);
}
```

The implementation uses the `hexi::endian::conditional_reverse` function which handles both integer and floating-point types (as seen in the code fragment that shows it handles `float` and `double` by bit-casting to integers, byteswapping, and then bit-casting back).

The function takes three parameters:
- The value to convert
- The source endianness
- The target endianness

By using `std::endian::native`, `std::endian::big`, and `std::endian::little`, we can easily specify the desired conversion direction for each function.

