Looking at the code fragments, I can see that Hexi provides buffer adaptors for reading and writing. Based on the usage patterns shown in the tests, here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_read_adaptor.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_write_adaptor.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

struct TypedData {
    uint32_t id;
    int16_t value;
    double ratio;
};

std::vector<uint8_t> write_typed_data(const TypedData& data) {
    std::vector<uint8_t> buffer;

    // Create a write adaptor for the buffer
    hexi::pmc::buffer_write_adaptor adaptor(buffer);

    // Write each field using the template write method
    adaptor.write(data.id);
    adaptor.write(data.value);
    adaptor.write(data.ratio);

    return buffer;
}

TypedData read_typed_data(const std::vector<uint8_t>& buffer) {
    TypedData data;

    // Create a read adaptor for the buffer
    hexi::pmc::buffer_read_adaptor adaptor(buffer);

    // Read each field in the same order they were written
    adaptor.read(&data.id);
    adaptor.read(&data.value);
    adaptor.read(&data.ratio);

    return data;
}
```

The implementation follows the patterns seen in the test files:
- `buffer_write_adaptor` is used for writing to a vector
- `buffer_read_adaptor` is used for reading from a vector  
- The template `write()` method is used to write different types directly
- The template `read(T* destination)` method is used to read into specific type pointers
- The order of operations matches between write and read functions

The adaptors handle the type-safe serialization/deserialization automatically, converting between the native types and their binary representation in the buffer.

